Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by James Okoro¶

Introduction¶

This project is an exploratory data analyses of the Prosper loan data set provided by Udacity. The data set contains information about loan listings and related variables including borrower as well as lender information. This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

This project is aimed at providing a summary of the features of certain variables that affect status of loans with an insight on the relationships among multiple variables using summary statistics and data visualizations. As such, answers can be provided to certain key questions related to the business or real-world context of the data.

There are two rating variables in our dataset: Credit grade and Prosper rating. Credit grade is the rating that was assigned at the time the listing went live. It is applicable for listings pre-2009 period and will only be populated for those listings. The Prosper Rating was assigned threafter and it is only applicable for loans originated after July 2009. For this analysis, both variables would be merged to a new single variable: credit rating.

In [400]:
# Merge both variables to a new one then drop them
df['credit_rating'] = df['credit_grade'].str.cat(df['prosper_rating'], na_rep='')
df = df.drop(['credit_grade', 'prosper_rating'], axis=1)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains 113,937 loans with 13 variables which are mainly numeric and categoric in nature. These variables are listed below:

Credit Rating: This is a combination of Credit Grade and Prosper Rating The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created and it is ordered as follows: N/A, HR, E, D, C, B, A, AA.

Loan Status: The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket.

Borrower APR: The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.

Loan Amount: The origination amount of the loan.

Employment Status: The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing.

Monthly Income: The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.

Term: The length of the loan expressed in months.

Income Range: The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created.

Listing Category: The category that uniquely identifies the listing to the public as displayed on the website.

Occupation: The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing.

Debt to Income Ratio: The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled. This value is Null if the debt to income ratio is not available. This value is capped at 10.01 (any debt to income ratio larger than 1000% will be returned as 1001%).

State: The two letter abbreviation of the state of the address of the borrower at the time the Listing was created.

Borrower Rate: The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

In this data set, I am interested in the factors affect that loan status and credit rating.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Loan status and credit rating have similar supporting factors since loans with good credit rating have a low tendency of default. The most important factors are borrower's APR (or interest rate), loan amount, income range, term and employment status. Other features we would review include debt-to-income ratio, listing category, borrower's state, monthly income and occupation.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I would be looking at the distribution of all the variables of the data set.

What is the Distribution of Loan Status?¶

First I would look at loan status, being the main variable of my analysis. There are a lot of categories on this variable which I would reduce by aggregating past due loans which only differ in delinquency period. Thereafter, I would arrange these categories in decreasing order of default.

In [410]:
# Aggregate Past Due loans 
df['loan_status'] = df['loan_status'].apply(lambda x: x if 'Past Due' not in x else 'Past Due') 
# Convert loan_status to a categorical variable 
status_dict = ['Completed', 'FinalPaymentInProgress', 'Current', 'Past Due', 'Defaulted', 'Chargedoff'] 
loan_status_order = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = status_dict) 
df['loan_status'] = df['loan_status'].astype(loan_status_order)

Now I have 6 categories of loan status: Completed, FinalPaymentInProgress, Current, Past Due, Defaulted and Chargedoff.

How are loans distributed across these categories?¶

In [411]:
# Create annotations
status_count = df['loan_status'].value_counts()
n_count = df['loan_status'].value_counts().sum()

base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
sb.countplot(data = df, x = 'loan_status', color = base_color)
# Get the tick locations and labels
locs, labels = plt.xticks(rotation=90)
# loop through each pair of locations and labels
for loc, label in zip(locs, labels): 
    # get the text property for the label to get the correct count 
    count = status_count[label.get_text()] 
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_count) 
    # print the annotation just above the top of the bar 
    plt.text(loc, count+200, pct_string, ha = 'center', color = 'black')
plt.title('Distribution of Loan Status')
plt.xlabel('Loan Status');

From the above chart, we see that about half of the loans are current, one-third are completed while 10.5% are charged-off loans.

How is Credit Rating Distributed?¶

Next, let us review how credit rating, being the second main variable of this analysis, is distributed.

In [412]:
# Plot ordinal distribution of credit rating
plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
sb.countplot(data = df, x = 'credit_rating', color = base_color)
plt.title('Distribution of Credit Rating')
plt.xlabel('Credit Rating');
# Add annotations by create a loop
rating_counts = df['credit_rating'].value_counts()
for i in range(rating_counts.shape[0]):
    count = rating_counts[i]
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_count)
    # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
    plt.text(i, count-1000, pct_string, ha = 'center', color = 'white');
plt.show()

From the above plot, the rating is distributed normally. We see a modal credit rating of C at 21%, a high risk rating HR at 9.2% and the highest credit rating AA at 7.8%.

In [414]:

plt.xscale('log')

plt.title('Log-scale Distribution of Loan Amount')
plt.show();

From the log-scale, the log-scale shows many spikes with much precision at certain round sums such as 1,000, 2,000, 3,000 etc. It peaked at 4,000 and trailed off quickly to the next spike. It is expected that loans applied for would be at round sums, so this distribution makes sense.

What is the Distribution of Borrower's APR and Rate?¶

Next, I'll look at the distribution of borrower's annual percentage rate (borrower's APR) and borrower's rate (interest rate).

In [415]:
# Create a function to plot numeric variables as percentage
def as_percent(df, column): # df is the dataset and column is the variable
    percent = (df[column].dropna().values)*100
    bins = np.arange(0, df[column].max()*100+binsize, binsize)
    plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
    plt.hist(x = percent, bins = bins)
    labels = ['{}'.format(v) for v in ticks]
    plt.xticks(ticks, labels)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 20)

First, I will start with the distribution of borrower's APR.

In [416]:

Next, what is the distribution of borrower's rate?

In [417]:

Both borrower's APR and interest rate have similar distribution which is almost normal and unimodal except for a spike at 35% and 31% for borrower's APR and interest rate respectively. Borrower's rate is borrower's annual percentage rate less service fees, hence, the similar distribution.

How is Debt-to-Income Ratio Distributed?¶

Next, the distribution of debt-to-income ratio would be plotted.

In [418]:

The above distribution is very narrow and highly right-skewed. This is because debt-to-income ratio is highly ranged from 0 to 10.01, however most values are less than 50%. I would split the data at 50% and consider them separately.

In [419]:
# Create a data set for debt-to-income ratio less than 50%

df_dtimin = df.loc[df_min,:]
In [420]:
# Create a data set for debt-to-income ratio of 50% and above
df_max = (df['debt_to_income_ratio'] >= 0.5) & (df['debt_to_income_ratio'] <= 10.01)
df_dtimax = df.loc[df_max,:]

For debt-to-income ratio less than 50%, we see an interesting normal distribution with a spike at 29% which similar to the plots of borrower's APR/rate. While, for that of 50% and above, it is very narrow and highly right-skewed and ranged to end with a short spike at 1001%.

plt.title('Distribution of Monthly Income')
plt.show();

Much details cannot be seen as the distribution is very narrow, highly-skewed and there are outliers as high as 1,750,000. So, lets plot it in a log-scale and exclude the outliers as well by limiting the x-axis to 50,000.

In [424]:
# Plot  using log-scale and truncate the x-axis to show only values less than 50k which makes the majority of data
log_binsize = 0.025
bins = 10 ** np.arange(3, 4.7, log_binsize)
plt.figure(figsize=[10, 5])
plt.hist(data = df, x = 'monthly_income', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([1e3, 2e3, 5e3, 1e4, 2e4, 5e4], ['1k', '2k','5k', '10k', '20k', '50k'])
plt.xlabel('Stated Monthly Income ($)')
plt.title('Truncated Log-Scale Distribution of Stated Monthly Income')
plt.show();

From the truncated log-scale, the distribution can be better interpreted as normal. It peaked at an income of 4,000 with 5,000 following closely with a lot of spikes at round sums as expected.

Interestingly, it appears that there are some relationships between the categorical variables and the numeric variables (borrower rate not included because of the similarity with borrower APR).

Credit Rating: Violin plots show that there is a positive correlation of borrower APR across the rating from AA to HR (High to Low). And inversely, a negative correlation of amount across the credit rating. Loans with high credit ratings have higher amounts with lower interest rates. It is important to note that amount, borrower APR and by extension borrower rate have a high effect on credit rating. There is no meaningful relationship with stated monthly income as we cannot ascertain much from the plot (due to wide range of distribution). Debt-to-income ratio was limited to values less than 0.5 so we could observe an almost even distribution with a slight drop at AA rating.

Loan Status: Chargedoff, defaulted and past due loans are seen to have higher borrower APR than others. The higher rates might be said to be affecting repayment which is a point to note. Loan amount on the average is lower for the loans that are delinquent. Debt-to-income ratio and stated monthly income have no relevant impact across the loan status except for a wide range of monthly income for current loans (probably as a result of outliers).

Income Range: As seen, there is a positive correlation for the monthly income and a wide range of values for 100,000 above category (probably as a result of high outliers). There is a negative correlation of borrower APR across the income ranges of 1-24,999 and 100,000+ which buttresses our point that the higher the income, the lower the interest rate. Once again, unemployed is seen to have a high borrower APR. And as expected, income range has a positive correlation with loan amount because the higher the income, the greater the loan original amount.

Employment Status: As shown, the unemployed borrow at higher rates than all other categories of employment. This is because of the high risk associated with their status of little or no stated monthly income and as expected, high debt-to-income ratio. Self employed are responsible for the wide range of stated monthly income and high outliers. This can be attributed to inability to compute their monthly income or capital inputted as income.

Conclusions¶

In this Prosper loan data exploration, the relationship between our main variables credit rating and loan status is significant. It was observed that most of the delinquent loans have poor rating as the lowest rating HR is evident among Defaulted loan status as well as Chargedoff and there is a decline across ratings for Chargedoff and Defaulted status.

For credit rating, I also observed a strong relationship with other features such as borrower's APR, amount and income range. There is a negative correlation of borrower's APR across the ratings from HR to AA and a positive correlation for amount. Thus highly rated loans have higher amounts with lower interest rates. For income range, lower credit ratings are highly represented in lower income ranges, thus, higher income ranges show better credit ratings.

Loan status is seemingly affected by amount, stated monthly income, borrower's APR, income range and debt-to-income ratio (when we limit it to values less than 1). Most delinquent loans (Chargedoff and Defaulted) have lower loan amounts, low monthly income, high debt-to-income ratio and lower income ranges.

From exploring other features, I verified the relationship between borrower's rate and APR to be positively correlated (correlation coefficient of 0.99). For employment status, I observed that the unemployed borrow at higher rates than all other categories of employment. Also Unemployed category have a high debt-to-income ratio and high borrower's APR. Self employed are responsible for the wide range of stated monthly income and high outliers. For Income Range, there is a positive correlation for the monthly income and a wide range of values for 100,000 above category. Also there is a negative correlation of borrower APR across the income ranges of 1-24,999 and 100,000+ which buttresses our point that the higher the income, the lower the interest rate. And as expected, income range has a positive correlation with loan amount because the higher the income, the greater the loan original amount. Most loans are 3-year termed, taken from the state of California and listed as debt consolidation. Most borrowers are listed as professionals.
